            <td style="font-family:&#39;Helvetica Neue&#39;,Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,sans-serif;border-collapse:collapse" width="580">
                
                        <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="580">
                            <tbody><tr style="border-collapse:collapse">
                                <td style="font-family:&#39;Helvetica Neue&#39;,Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,sans-serif;border-collapse:collapse" width="580">
                                    <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:24px;color:#b2a78c;font-weight:bold;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:18px;font-family:&#39;Helvetica Neue&#39;,Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,sans-serif" align="left">

Umati Project: Final Report Release</p>
                                    <div style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444;margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:18px;font-family:&#39;Helvetica Neue&#39;,Arial,Helvetica,Geneva,sans-serif" align="left">
                                        <p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	For nine months, between September 2012 and May 2013,  Ushahidi teamed up with iHub Research to create Umati (Swahili for &quot;crowd&quot;) - a media monitoring project that collects and examines multi-lingual incidences of hate and dangerous speech in the Kenyan online space.</p>


<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	As a close to the first phase of the project, we hereby release the final report, which discusses Umati&#39;s main findings, offers a methodology for online media monitoring that can be replicated in other countries and contexts, and provides a basis for further research.</p>


<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	Some of the findings, which are discussed at greater length in this report, include:</p>
<ul style="margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:18px;margin-left:19px;padding-top:0;padding-bottom:0;padding-right:0;padding-left:0">
	<li style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444">
		The occurence of online hate speech cannot solely be relied on as a precursor to violence on the ground.</li>
	<li style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444">
		<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
			Most Kenyans online prefer to converse in English, Kiswahili, Sheng or Kenyan English slang. There were very few hate speech statements that were purely in vernacular.</p>
	</li>
	<li style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444">
		<i>KOT cuffing</i> contributed to having only 3% of total comments from Twitter, while 90% were from Facebook.</li>
	<li style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444">
		<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
			There is a huge disparity between what the public perceives as hate speech and what the Umati project defines it as.</p>
	</li>
	<li style="font-size:13px;line-height:18px;color:#444444">
		<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
			The Benesch framework offered a good basis for the definition of dangerous speech. Umati went a step further to refine the definition to suit the Kenyan context.</p>
	</li>
</ul>
<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	Click <a href="http://ushahidicom.createsend1.com/t/y-l-tyjkuiy-yhmtlyhlr-e/" style="color:#b2a78c;font-weight:bold;text-decoration:none" target="_blank">here</a> to access the full report. </p>
<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	We thank you for your support and feedback throughout the project, and look forward to contributing to further research in this area.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	Best,</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	Umati, iHub Research and Ushahidi.</p>
<p style="margin-bottom:15px">
	 </p>
